I'm not a huge fan of this one. In the early game, you often won't be able to keep vuln+weak+doom up consistently, and even if you do draw this at the right time it's only twice as strong as a strike. That's very good, but if you draw it at the wrong time, it's actually worse than a strike, so overall it's not as good at consistent damage output as a lot of Collector's other attacks, most of which have an additional benefit on top of their damage.
In later acts, it can consistently deal a lot of damage, but at that point I generally don't need cards that are just a stronger version of Strike with no other benefit. This card is always decent, but never quite good enough that I would take it frequently.

Keep in mind that to get three hits of damage with this and You Are Mine, you need to spend three energy in one turn. That's a pretty steep cost in the early game, even if you got an energy relic from a boss swap. And if you draw this on a different turn from YAM and don't have another source of debuffs, then this is either 0 or 4 damage.

messages.content: then there's omen which makes it a complete build

This card is in a weird place overall, and I largely agree with K37's assessment. In the early game, you need more consistent frontloaded damage cards than this, because the fail case of it doing 0 or 4 damage is abysmal at that point. Later on in the run, sure you might have more energy, more access to debuffs (especially if you are running doom/affliction), and more strength to pay this out, but are you really looking to take a pure damage card at that point? On collector, who has access to 3 incredibly strong single card damage scaling solutions for the late game (omen, empower, Dark Lord Form)? It's a great payoff alongside those damage scaling cards, but it's also totally unnecessary. If you have massive amounts of strength scaling, you could just kill the enemies with strikes, or whatever damage focused cards you took in the early game, there's no need to add a card like this. 

So when do you take this? In the midgame if you have tons of debuffs/strength, but not quite enough damage focused cards I suppose. If you have runic pyramid, hexx talisman, or some other way to line up debuffs alongside it, then it's more takeable, and I could see using it to deal heavy damage in act 2 to burst down difficult fights with the right setup. I think that's a very rare spot to find yourself in though, and even in that spot, there's still an element of unreliability at play. You kind of need to be able to consistently keep up 2 debuffs for this to acceptable, and get 3 up often enough for it to be worth the inherent risk of 0 and 1. Do you take it in act 3 if you have strong debuff application, but haven't found any of the other major scaling solutions?

Upgrade is a solid +2, which goes up to a +4 and beyond if you applying multiple debuffs (and you probably shouldn't be taking this card if you can't). Very good upgrade if the card was good enough to include originally. Any sources of strength from relics is multiplied by this, and red mask/bag or marbles helps it a bit.
